ðŸ”¹1. Algorithm
Compute the total sum of the array.

Traverse the array from left to right, maintaining a running prefix sum.

For each index i, check if:
prefixSum == totalSum - prefixSum
This means prefix and suffix have equal sums.

If such a point is found, return true.
If no such point is found after the loop, return false.

ðŸ”¹2. Java Program
public static boolean canSplit(int[] arr) {
        int totalSum = 0;
        for (int num : arr) {
            totalSum += num;
        }

        int prefixSum = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) { 
            prefixSum += arr[i];
            int suffixSum = totalSum - prefixSum;

            if (prefixSum == suffixSum) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

ðŸ”¹3. Time and Space Complexity

Task	              Complexity
Time Complexity	    O(n)
Space Complexity	  O(1)

ðŸ”¹4. Example Walkthrough
Input:
arr = {1, 2, 3, 3}
Steps:
totalSum = 9

Traverse:

i = 0 â†’ prefix = 1, suffix = 8 âŒ
i = 1 â†’ prefix = 3, suffix = 6 âŒ
i = 2 â†’ prefix = 6, suffix = 3 âŒ
i = 3 â†’ Not allowed (suffix would be empty)

At i = 2:
prefixSum = 6, suffixSum = 3 â†’ not equal

BUT actually:

prefixSum = 3, suffixSum = 6 at i = 1
prefix = [1,2], suffix = [3,3] âœ…

So correct check is up to i < arr.length - 1

âœ… Output:
Can split arr1? true
Can split arr2? false
